
[1]downwards

   DOWNWARD, DOWNWARDS, adv. [See Ward.]

   1. From a higher place to a lower; in a descending course, whether
   directly toward the center of the earth, or not; as, to tend downward;
   to move or roll downwards; to look downward; to take root downwards.

   2. In a course or direction from a head, spring, origin or source.
   Water flows downward toward the sea; we sailed downward on the stream.

   3. In a course of lineal descent from an ancestor, considered as a
   head; as, to trace successive generations downward from Adam or
   Abraham.

   4. In the course of falling or descending from elevation or
   distinction.
